<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sets-of-real-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sets of Real Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m>A,B\subseteq\R</m> and <m>c\in\R</m>. We use the following set
      operations:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>A+B:=\{a+b : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>
      <li><m>AB:=\{ab : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>
      <li><m>cA:=\{c\}A=\{ca : a\in A\}</m></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      In particular, <m>-A=\{-a : a\in A\}=\{a : -a\in A\}</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-bounded-subsets">
    <title>Bounded Subsets of <m>\R</m></title>

    <p>
      A real number <m>b</m> is an <term>upper bound</term><idx><h>upper
      bound</h></idx> (resp. a <term>lower bound</term><idx><h>lower
      bound</h></idx>) of a set of real numbers <m>A</m> if <m>b \ge a</m>
      (resp. <m>b \le a</m>) for every <m>a \in A</m>. Note that <m>b</m>
      is an upper bound of <m>A</m> if and only if <m>-b</m> is a lower
      bound of <m>-A</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      A set of real numbers <m>A</m> is <term>bounded
      above</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>above</h></idx> (resp. <term>bounded
      below</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>below</h></idx>) if it
      has an upper bound (resp. a lower bound). We say <m>A</m> is
      <term>bounded</term><idx><h>bounded</h></idx> if it is both bounded
      above and bounded below.
     </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-bounded-subsets-examples">
      <statement>
        <ul>
	  <li>
	    The interval <m>(0,1)</m> is bounded since, for example, it is
	    bounded above by <m>1</m> and bounded below by <m>0</m>.
	  </li>

	  <li> The set <m>\{x^{-1} \colon x \lt 0\}</m> is bounded below,
	  for example by <m>0</m>, but not bounded above.  </li>

	  <li>
	  <m>\Z</m> is neither bounded below nor above.
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    Every real number is both an upper bound and a lower bound of
	    the empty set <m>\emptyset</m>.
	  </li>
	</ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
	If <m>b</m> is an upper bound of <m>A</m>, then it is also an upper
	bound of every subset of <m>A</m>. Consequently, an arbitrary
	intersection of sets bounded above is again bounded above. Suppose
	<m>A</m> and <m>A'</m> are bounded above by <m>a</m> and <m>a'</m>,
	respectively. Then <m>A \cup A'</m> is bounded above by
	<m>\max\{a,a'\}</m>. Thus, a finite union of sets bounded above is
	bounded above. Likewise, the collection of subsets of <m>\R</m> that
	are bounded below (resp. bounded) is closed under arbitrary
	intersection and finite union. In particular, every finite set of
	real numbers is bounded.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-bounded-iff-abs-bound">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A set <m>A \subseteq \R</m> is bounded if and only if there exists
          <m>M\in\R</m> such that <m>|a|\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement> 
      <proof>
	<p>
	  If <m>|a|\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>, then <m>-M\le a\le M</m>
	  for all <m>a\in A</m>. Hence <m>A</m> is bounded below by <m>-M</m>
	  and bounded above by <m>M</m>.
	</p> 

	<p>
	  Conversely, if <m>A</m> is bounded, then so is <m>-A</m>. Hence
	  <m>A \cup -A</m> is bounded, and therefore its subset <m>|A|</m> is
	  bounded as well. Let <m>M</m> be an upper bound of <m>|A|</m>. Then
	  <m>|a|\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-intervals">
    <title>Intervals</title>
    
    <p>
      An interval is a subset of <m>\R</m> of one of the following forms
      (<m>a \le b \in \R</m>):
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>(a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b):=\{x\in\R \colon x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>\R=(-\infty,\infty)</m></li>
    </ul>
    

    <p>
      An interval <m>I</m> contains every point between any two of its
      elements. In other words, <m>[x,y] \subseteq I</m> whenever <m>x,y \in
      I</m> with <m>x \le y</m>. Conversely, any subset of <m>\R</m> with
      this property is an interval. A <term>nondegenerate interval</term>
      is an interval with at least two points.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-interval-cardinality-r">
      <statement>
        <p>
	  Every nondegenerate interval <m>I\subseteq\R</m> has cardinality
	  <m>|\R|</m>. In particular, it is uncountable.
	</p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p>
	  Every such interval <m>I</m> contains an open interval
	  <m>(a,b)</m> and is a subset of <m>\R</m>.  It is enough to
	  show <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>.  The map <m>x\mapsto (x-c)/r</m>
	  with <m>c=(a+b)/2</m>, <m>r=(b-a)/2</m>, is a bijection
	  <m>(a,b)\to(-1,1)</m>.  Also <m>t\mapsto\tan(\pi t/2)</m> is
	  a bijection <m>(-1,1)\to\R</m>.  Hence <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>,
	  so <m>|I|=|\R|</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-intersection-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The intersection of two intervals is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p> Let <m>I,J</m> be intervals. Since <m>\emptyset</m> and singletons
	are intervals, we may assume <m>I \cap J</m> has at least two points
	<m>x&lt;y</m>. Since <m>I</m> and <m>J</m> are intervals, <m>[x,y]</m>
	is a subset of both <m>I</m> and <m>J</m>, and hence of <m>I\cap J</m>.
	Thus, <m>I\cap J</m> is an interval.
	</p>
      </proof>

      </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-union-overlapping-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The union of two overlapping intervals is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
	<p>
	  Let <m>I,J</m> be two overlapping intervals, and pick <m>a \in I
	  \cap J</m>. If <m>I \cup J</m> is a singleton, then we are done.
	  Otherwise, we can take <m>x \lt y</m> in <m>I \cup J</m>. We must
	  show <m>[x,y] \subseteq I \cup J</m>. If both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
	  lie in the same interval, then <m>[x,y]</m> is a subset of that
	  interval, hence of <m>I \cup J</m>. Otherwise, after relabeling
	  we may assume <m>x \in I \setminus J</m> and <m>y \in J \setminus
	  I</m>. If <m>a \lt x</m>, then <m>x \in [a,y] \subseteq J</m>,
	  a contradiction. If <m>y \lt a</m>, then <m>y \in [x,a] \subseteq
	  I</m>, a contradiction. Therefore <m>x \le a \le y</m>. Then we
	  have <m>[x,a] \subseteq I</m> and <m>[a,y] \subseteq J</m>. Hence
	  <m>[x,y]=[x,a]\cup[a,y]\subseteq I\cup J</m>, so <m>I\cup J</m>
	  is an interval.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

</section>
